<!-- inc publications_db -->

 <strong>January 21,  2014</strong><p><i>Orange County Register</i><p><strong>Toddlers & Tablets</strong><p><strong>By: Marcie Taylor</strong><br><p><!--
<P>
<I>Read the story below or view it on the 
<A HREF="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/">OC Register</A> website.</I>
-->





<P>
For Hollie Eisenman of Orange, the iPad was a
lifesaver for her family when they traveled from
Orange County to Oregon with her 21?2-year-old
twin daughters. The girls, Katelyn and Chelsea,
could turn their iPads on and find their favorite
games by themselves.
<P>
&ldquo;We live in a very different world today than we
did just 20 years ago, and it seems more important
for kids to be technology savvy than to be
able to write in cursive (these days),&rdquo; Eisenman
said. &ldquo;They don&rsquo;t use the iPads very often, but
when they do, it is always educational.&rdquo;
<P>
A recent survey by the nonprofit family advocacy
organization Common Sense Media, in a
poll of 1,463 parents with children under age 8,
found that 38 percent of children 2 years old and
younger have used a mobile device, up 10 percent
from two years ago. The survey also showed that
children are using these devices &ndash; particularly



tablets &ndash; more often than ever for activities
such as watching shows, playing games and
using apps.
<P>
Lilledeshan Bose of Riverside has a son,
Jah, 3, who started using an iPad at 18
months.
<P>
&ldquo;He started out with games by Duck
Duck Moose and now he goes on YouTube,&rdquo;
she said. &ldquo;We use it at restaurants or in
friends&rsquo; houses when we want him in one
place.&rdquo;
<P>
Bose voiced her concern about Jah&rsquo;s attention
span, people skills, imagination and
introspection.
<P>
In a 2013 interview with Mashable, Common
Sense Media founder and CEO Jim
Steyer said, &ldquo;We need to make screen time
learning time. Technology used wisely is an
essential element to education.&rdquo;
<P>
<STRONG>Mimi Ito</STRONG>, a cultural
anthropologist
at UC Irvine,
agrees. &ldquo;Tablets
and other portable
touch-screen devices
have opened
up a host of new opportunities
as well
as interesting new
challenges for parents
of young children.&rdquo;
<P>
What effect this
is having on young
children is unclear.
&ldquo;The devices just
haven&rsquo;t been around long enough for us to
really know if it is harmful or beneficial for
little ones to have access from an early
age,&rdquo; Ito said.
<P>
The secret might be in finding a balance.
<P>
Carrie and Nick Braun have two children
who use tablets. &ldquo;Our almost
3-year-old, Ryan, watched his older sister,
Abby, use the iPad, and he just took it on
himself,&rdquo; Carrie Braun said.
Ryan enjoys Disney Junior Appisodes,
&ldquo;Monkey Preschool Lunchbox,&rdquo; &ldquo;Veggietales&rdquo;
and &ldquo;Paint Sparkle.&rdquo; The Brauns say
they limit his screen time to 20-minute sessions
at most, once a day.
<P>
&ldquo;Sometimes he and his sister watch yoga
videos together. I like that they are using
the iPad to do something active,&rdquo; their
mother said. &ldquo;We believe that with appropriate
limits on time and the type of information
they can access, tablets can be a
great opportunity for toddlers to learn
computer skills and engage in fun that can
be educational. We try to be good examples
and are mindful not to be buried on the iPad
or on our smartphones all day!&rdquo;
<P>
Many teachers, including Melissa Guerin,
a kindergarten teacher in Costa Mesa,
love the resources that technology offers.
<P>
&ldquo;There&rsquo;s nothing like a video game or letter-
tracing app to help a child learn,&rdquo; she
said. &ldquo;It keeps their attention and it&rsquo;s fun!&rdquo;
<P>
However, it doesn&rsquo;t replace human interaction.
Guerin, a mother of two toddler
boys, advises parents that if they are going
to allow their child to use a tablet, choose
an educational app and limit their time.
<P>
&ldquo;Technology is great, it is fun and helpful,
but it&rsquo;s very addicting,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;And
so it has to be used in moderation with
young children and monitored by an adult.&rdquo;
<P>
The American Academy of Pediatrics
recommends that parents establish
&ldquo;screen-free&rdquo; zones at home by making
sure there are no TVs, computers or video
games in children&rsquo;s bedrooms and by turning
off the TV during dinner.
<P>
&ldquo;Television and other entertainment
media should be avoided for infants and
children under age 2 because a child&rsquo;s brain
develops rapidly during these first years,
and young children
learn best by interacting
with people,
not screens,&rdquo; the
group advises.
<P>
Ito agrees that
children younger
than 2 don&rsquo;t really
need access to
screen-based media
and cautions about
overall rules on
screen time.
<P>
&ldquo;Today&rsquo;s digital devices
can be used in
so many different
ways and have such
diverse forms of content that it isn&rsquo;t wise to
regulate them purely based on screen or
device time,&rdquo; Ito said. &ldquo;A healthy environment
for kids includes novel inputs that
media can provide, as well as reducing the
stresses of family life. Parents shouldn&rsquo;t be
racked with guilt if they hand a toddler an
iPad during a plane ride or a long wait in
line, or introduce some interactive phonics
games for an early reader.&rdquo;
<P>
Ito believes children today need to develop
the capacity at earlier ages to begin to
self-regulate media choices.
<P>
&ldquo;Just like the decision to introduce kids
to ice cream or chocolate, I don&rsquo;t think
there is a single rule that is going to work
for all parents. But it is going to be a give
and take between the family&rsquo;s values and
routines and the wider world that the child
will eventually be exposed to,&rdquo; Ito said.
&ldquo;Even in the most protective families, a
child is going to discover sweets and interactive
games. When that happens, they
need to be able to consume in moderation,
and eventually they will need to
engage
without parental regulation.&rdquo;





<br><TITLE>Toddlers & Tablets</TITLE>

</div>
</blockquote>
